SIMPLE: coalition
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Coalition
<hw>Co`a*li"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL.
<ets>coalitio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>coalition</ets>. See
<er>Coalesce</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of coalescing; union
into a body or mass, as of separate bodies or parts; <as>as, a
<ex>coalition</ex> of atoms</as>.</def> <rj><au>Bentley.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 271 --></p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A combination, for temporary purposes, of persons,
parties, or states, having different interests.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>coalition</qex> of the puritan and the blackleg.</q>
<rj><qau>J. Randolph.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>coalition</qex> between the religious and worldly enemies
of popery.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Alliance; confederation; confederacy; league;
combination; conjunction; conspiracy; union.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Coalitioner</ent>⟦br⟧
